The paper discusses centrality measures and their importance in complex networks, which is a topic that falls under the scope of social and information networks (cs.SI) and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The proposed methods for estimating centrality rank using sampling techniques and machine learning models suggest a focus on statistical learning (cs.LG) and systems and control (cs.SY). The paper also mentions the dynamic nature of real-world networks, which could suggest a potential fit for the sub-category of software engineering (cs.SE).
